Narrative Log - 2026-05-06

This was a day of reducing slack in the system.

The visible part was the Guardian shell. A nested card layer came out, the thread rail cleanup was finished, and the compact tiles were restored after the regression. On the surface that sounds cosmetic, but it matters because the chat shell is one of the places where structural confusion becomes user confusion very quickly. The goal was not decoration. It was to make the interface stop implying depth and grouping that were not actually helping the conversation flow.

Underneath that, the more important work was boundary hardening. Graph-write adapter failures were bound at the store boundary, which is the right place for them to become legible. That shifts the system away from vague upstream collapse and toward explicit failure handling. When a write path fails, it should fail where the responsibility lives. That is a small change with real operational value because it gives us a cleaner place to reason about retries, diagnostics, and future recovery behavior.

The runtime proof work continued in parallel. Image routing truth was stamped and propagated through live turns, then the containment trace and image-routing absence were promoted into the evidence trail. The related proof docs were rerun and updated accordingly. This is the kind of work that does not add flash, but it removes drift. It keeps the documentation from outrunning the runtime and makes the release story harder to fake. That is especially important here because beta truth still depends on the live stack matching the supported path, not just on the existence of polished docs.

There was also a smaller but meaningful release-context cleanup around default cloud bases and release-hold checks. That kept the gating logic focused on the supported local-first posture instead of letting unrelated defaults muddy the signal. In a system like this, the dangerous failure mode is not always a crash. Sometimes it is a misleading sense of readiness. Today’s work pushed back against that.

The shape of the day, then, was not feature growth. It was truth alignment. The UI became flatter and more honest, the runtime routing story became more explicit, and the proof record got closer to the system it describes. That leaves us in a better place for the next round of live validation, because the remaining gaps are clearer and the false ones are smaller.

What this makes possible next is straightforward: re-run the live supported-path proof against the exact current tip, verify the backend posture again, and keep tightening the coding-result return path until the evidence is live rather than just structural.





